{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14447"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14447"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.12,0.71,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103674"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86091"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"3341"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103674"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after being found confused and agitated by her roommate. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. She is diaphoretic and tremulous with dilated but reactive pupils. Neurological examination reveals hyperreflexia and inducible clonus in both lower extremities. She has had three episodes of diarrhoea since arrival.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn further questioning, the roommate mentions finding several empty medication bottles in the patient\u0027s room but cannot recall the names of the medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications has this patient most likely taken?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diazepam","Quetiapine","Fluoxetine","Oxycodone","Aspirin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is highly suggestive of serotonin syndrome, making \u003Cstrong\u003Efluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E, a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI), the most likely medication taken by the patient. Serotonin syndrome is characterised by a triad of symptoms: mental status changes (confusion, agitation), autonomic hyperactivity (tachycardia, hypertension, hyperthermia, diaphoresis), and neuromuscular abnormalities (hyperreflexia, clonus, tremor). The presence of dilated pupils and diarrhoea further supports this diagnosis. Importantly, serotonin syndrome has an acute onset, typically within hours of drug ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E, a benzodiazepine, in overdose typically causes central nervous system depression with drowsiness, confusion, ataxia, and respiratory depression. Pupils are usually normal-sized or slightly constricted. Importantly, benzodiazepine overdose does not cause hyperreflexia, clonus, hyperthermia, or diarrhoea - instead, reflexes are typically diminished.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E, an atypical antipsychotic, in overdose commonly causes sedation, tachycardia, and orthostatic hypotension, and mild hyperthermia. Quetiapine overdose may also cause QT prolongation on ECG. Like all antipsychotics, it may cause neuroleptic malignant syndrome (NMS) which is a life-threatening condition \u2013 however, NMS is more common with typical antipsychotics, like haloperidol. Differences of NMS to serotonin syndrome include more insidious onset over days to weeks, presenting with lead-pipe rigidity rather than hyperreflexia, hyporeflexia rather than clonus, and normal-sized pupils. Additionally, gastrointestinal symptoms like diarrhoea are not features of NMS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E, an opioid analgesic, in overdose classically presents with the triad of decreased consciousness, respiratory depression, and pinpoint pupils. This patient\u0027s dilated pupils, hyperreflexia, hyperthermia, and diarrhoea are all inconsistent with opioid toxicity. Opioid overdose typically causes hyporeflexia rather than hyperreflexia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E overdose causes salicylate toxicity, which presents with tinnitus, altered mental status, hyperthermia, and a characteristic mixed respiratory alkalosis and metabolic acidosis. While confusion and hyperthermia may be present, aspirin overdose does not cause the specific neuromuscular findings of hyperreflexia, clonus, or dilated pupils seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Hunter criteria for diagnosing serotonin syndrome require exposure to a serotonergic agent plus one of the following: spontaneous clonus, inducible clonus with agitation or diaphoresis, ocular clonus with agitation or diaphoresis, tremor and hyperreflexia, or hypertonia with temperature above 38\u00b0C and ocular or inducible clonus. This patient meets multiple criteria. Management involves discontinuation of the offending agent and supportive care with close monitoring of hyperthermia and autonomic instability. Benzodiazepines may be used for agitation, and in severe cases, serotonin antagonists like cyproheptadine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Serotonin syndrome is characterized by a triad of mental status changes, autonomic hyperactivity, and neuromuscular abnormalities.","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome presents with hyporeflexia, lead-pipe rigidity, and has an insidious onset","Benzodiazepine overdose causes CNS depression with normal-sized pupils, while opioid overdose causes pinpoint pupils and respiratory depression."],"references":["Simon LV, Torrico TJ, Keenaghan M. Serotonin Syndrome. [Updated 2024 Mar 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482377/","Scotton WJ, Hill LJ, Williams AC, Barnes NM. Serotonin Syndrome: Pathophysiology, Clinical Features, Management, and Potential Future Directions. Int J Tryptophan Res. 2019 Sep 9;12:1178646919873925. doi: 10.1177/1178646919873925. PMID: 31523132; PMCID: PMC6734608. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6734608/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86091"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14447"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86091"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T16:10:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T16:11:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7142"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103674"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}